Data Preprocessing

df <- read.csv("OnlineNewsPopularity.csv", header = TRUE)
df <- df[, !(names(df) == "url")] # removing the URL column
df_factor <- df

# change categorical variables to factor type
cat_cols <- c("weekday_is_monday", "weekday_is_tuesday", "weekday_is_wednesday", "weekday_is_thursday", "weekday_is_friday", "weekday_is_saturday", "weekday_is_sunday", "is_weekend", "data_channel_is_lifestyle", "data_channel_is_entertainment", "data_channel_is_bus", "data_channel_is_socmed", "data_channel_is_tech", "data_channel_is_world")
df_factor[, cat_cols] <- lapply(df_factor[, cat_cols], as.factor)

# turn shares into binary variable w/ threshold 1400 (df_factor only)
df_popular <- df_factor
threshold <- 1400
df_popular$popularity <- ifelse(df_popular$shares >= threshold, 1, 0)
df_popular <- df_popular[, !(names(df_popular) == "shares")] # removing the shares column

Model Development for Regression

Model Selection

I decided to compare bagging, random forest, and GBM models. I started with a bagging model as it is the simplest to interpret while still being able to handle complex relationships. This model can be computationally expensive, especially given the number of predictors in this data set. Moving to random forests, this model is not as simple to interpret, however can reduce overfitting because of its random feature selection. I thought this would be a good model given the number of features in the article data set, as the data is unlikely to be linear and random forests are robust to noisy data. Finally GBM models can acheive high predictive accuracy and remains robust to nosiy data. It however can be very computationally expensive and requires careful hyperparametric tuning to acheive optimal performance.

Model Development

B <- 100 
n <- nrow(df_factor)
pred <- matrix(NA, nrow = n, ncol = B)

for (i in 1:B) {
    set.seed(i) 
    train_idx <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE)
    oob_idx <- setdiff(1:n, train_idx)
    
    train_bag <- df_factor[train_idx, ]
    oob <- df_factor[oob_idx, ]
   
    bag_model <- rpart(shares~., data = train_bag, method = "anova", cp = 0)
    pred[oob_idx, i] <- predict(bag_model, oob)
}

# Calculate OOB mspe
yhat_bag <- rowMeans(pred, na.rm = TRUE, dims = 1)
bag_mspe <- mean((df_factor$shares - yhat_bag)^2)
bag_rmse <- sqrt(bag_mspe)
n = nrow(df_factor)
mspe <- rep(NA, 5)

for (i in 1:5) {
    set.seed(i)
    train_idx <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE)
    test_idx <- setdiff(1:n, train_idx)
    
    train_rf <- df_factor[train_idx, ]
    test_rf <- df_factor[test_idx, ]
    
    rf_model <- randomForest(shares ~ ., data = train_rf, ntree = 100)
    yhat_rf <- predict(rf_model, test_rf)
    
    # Calculate OOB MSPE
    mspe[i] <- mean((test_rf$shares - yhat_rf)^2)
}

rf_rmse <- sqrt(mean(mspe))
# create hyperparameter grid
grid <- expand.grid(
  shrinkage = c(0.01, 0.1, 0.3),
  interaction.depth = c(1, 3, 5),
  optimal_trees = 0,               # a place to dump results
  min_RMSE = 0                     # a place to dump results
)

for (i in 1:nrow(grid)) {
  gbm.tune <- gbm(
    formula = shares ~ .,
    distribution = "gaussian",
    data = df,
    n.trees = 1500,
    interaction.depth = grid$interaction.depth[i],
    shrinkage = grid$shrinkage[i],
    cv.folds = 10,
    n.cores = NULL, # will use all cores by default
    verbose = FALSE
  )
  # add min training error and trees to grid
  grid$optimal_trees[i] <- which.min(gbm.tune$cv.error)
  grid$min_RMSE[i] <- sqrt(min(gbm.tune$cv.error))
  
}
best_params <- grid %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(min_RMSE) %>%
  head(1)

# train GBM model
gbm.final <- gbm(
  formula = shares ~ .,
  distribution = "gaussian",
  data = df_factor,
  n.trees = best_params$optimal_trees,
  interaction.depth = best_params$interaction.depth,
  shrinkage = best_params$shrinkage,
  train.fraction = 1,
  cv.folds = 0,
  n.cores = NULL, # will use all cores by default
  verbose = FALSE
  )  
rmspe <- c()

for (i in 1:100) {
  ind <- unique(sample(1:nrow(df_factor), nrow(df_factor), replace = TRUE))  
  train_gbm <- df_factor[ind, ]
  test_gbm <- df_factor[-ind, ]
  
  gbm.final <- gbm(
    formula = shares ~ .,
    distribution = "gaussian",
    data = train_gbm,
    n.trees = 1000,
    interaction.depth = best_params$interaction.depth,
    shrinkage = best_params$shrinkage,
    train.fraction = 1,
    cv.folds = 0,
    n.cores = NULL, # will use all cores by default
    verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  yhat_gbm <- predict(gbm.final, test_gbm, n.trees = best_params$optimal_trees)
  rmspe[i] <- sqrt(mean((test_gbm$shares - yhat_gbm)^2))
}

GBM_rmse <- mean(rmspe)

Model Development for Classification

BAGGING, RANDOM FOREST & LPM

Bagging can handle multiple factors that may influence popularity by generating multiple bootstrap samples from the original dataset and training a base model on each sample.

Random forest is an extension of bagging that uses decision trees as a base model. Random forest is able to handle high-dimensional feature spaces and nonlinear relationships.

While LPM is simpler in comparison to bagging and random forest, it offers identifications of direct correlations between specific features and popularity that can better inform marketing strategies. LPM is useful in classification models as it predicts the probability of a binary outcome (popular or non-popular).

Based on the summary output, we can refine the model by selecting only the variables that have statistically significant coefficients (i.e., p-value < 0.05) and excluding those with NA coefficients due to singularities.

In summary, Bagging, Random Forest and LPM are suitable in predicting popularity. Bagging and random forest offer improved performance through learning and can handle complex datasets, while LPM provides interpretability and insights into linear relationships

Model Development

set.seed(1)
AUC_lpm <- c()


for (i in 1:50) {
  ind <- unique(sample(nrow(df_popular), nrow(df_popular), replace = TRUE))
  train <- df_popular[ind, ]
  test <- df_popular[-ind, ]
  
  # Fit Linear Probability Model (LPM)
 model <- glm(popularity ~ n_tokens_title + n_non_stop_unique_tokens + num_hrefs + num_self_hrefs + average_token_length + num_keywords + data_channel_is_entertainment + data_channel_is_bus + data_channel_is_socmed + data_channel_is_tech + kw_min_min + kw_avg_min + kw_min_max + kw_max_avg + kw_avg_avg + self_reference_min_shares + weekday_is_monday + weekday_is_tuesday + weekday_is_wednesday + weekday_is_thursday + weekday_is_friday + weekday_is_saturday + LDA_00 + LDA_01 + LDA_02 + LDA_03 + global_subjectivity + title_subjectivity + title_sentiment_polarity + abs_title_subjectivity, family = binomial, data = train)

  
  phat_lpm <- predict(model, test, type = "response")
  
  # Exclude NAs in predictions
  phat_lpm <- pmin(pmax(phat_lpm, 0), 1, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  # Calculate LPM AUC
  pred_rocr <- prediction(phat_lpm, test$popularity)
  auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocr, measure = "auc")
  AUC_lpm[i] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
}
mean_AUC_lpm <- mean(AUC_lpm)
cat("Mean AUC for LPM:", mean_AUC_lpm, "\n")
## Mean AUC for LPM: 0.704401
# Plot AUC for LPM with confidence intervals
plot(AUC_lpm, ylab = "AUC", col = "green", ylim = c(min(AUC_lpm) - 0.01, max(AUC_lpm) + 0.01))
abline(h = mean(AUC_lpm), col = "red", lwd = 2)
abline(h = mean(AUC_lpm) + 2 * sd(AUC_lpm), col = "blue")
abline(h = mean(AUC_lpm) - 2 * sd(AUC_lpm), col = "blue")

predictions <- ifelse(phat_lpm > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Create confusion matrix
lpm_conf_matrix <- table(predictions, test$popularity)

# Calculate accuracy
lpm_accuracy <- sum(diag(lpm_conf_matrix)) / sum(lpm_conf_matrix)

# Calculate precision
lpm_precision <- lpm_conf_matrix[2, 2] / sum(lpm_conf_matrix[, 2])

# Calculate recall
lpm_recall <- lpm_conf_matrix[2, 2] / sum(lpm_conf_matrix[2, ])

# Calculate F1 score
lpm_f1_score <- 2 * (lpm_precision * lpm_recall) / (lpm_precision + lpm_recall)
B <- 100
set.seed(1)
ind <- sample(nrow(df_popular), nrow(df_popular) * 0.8)
train_bag_class <- df_popular[ind, ]
test_bag_class <- df_popular[-ind, ]

#Initialize matrices
phat3 <- matrix(0, B, nrow(test_bag_class))
bagging_AUC <- c()
OOB_errors <- numeric(B)

for (i in 1:B) {
   set.seed(i)
   
   
   idx <- sample(nrow(train_bag_class), nrow(train_bag_class), replace = TRUE)
   dt <- train_bag_class[idx, ]
   
   
   fit <- rpart(
     popularity ~ n_tokens_title + n_non_stop_unique_tokens + num_hrefs + num_self_hrefs + average_token_length + num_keywords + data_channel_is_entertainment + data_channel_is_bus + data_channel_is_socmed + data_channel_is_tech + kw_min_min + kw_avg_min + kw_min_max + kw_max_avg + kw_avg_avg + self_reference_min_shares + weekday_is_monday + weekday_is_tuesday + weekday_is_wednesday + weekday_is_thursday + weekday_is_friday + weekday_is_saturday + LDA_00 + LDA_01 + LDA_02 + LDA_03 + global_subjectivity + title_subjectivity + title_sentiment_polarity + abs_title_subjectivity,
     cp = 0,
     data = dt,
     method = "class"
   )
   
   #Predict OOB
   phat3[i, ] <- predict(fit, test_bag_class, type = "prob")[, 2]
   
   #Calculate OOB error 
   OOB_errors[i] <- mean(ifelse(phat3[i, ] > 0.5, 1, 0) != test_bag_class$popularity)

   
   phat_f <- colMeans(phat3[1:i, , drop = FALSE])  
  
  
   #AUC
   pred_rocr <- prediction(phat_f, test_bag_class$popularity)
   auc_ROCR <- performance(pred_rocr, measure = "auc")
   bagging_AUC[i] <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
}
 
#Calculate the mean AUC over all iterations
bagging_mean_AUC <- mean(bagging_AUC)
 
#Overall OOB confusion matrix
oob_pred <- as.factor(ifelse(colMeans(phat3) > 0.5, "1", "0"))
oob_actual <- as.factor(test_bag_class$popularity)
overall_OOB_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(oob_pred, oob_actual)
 
#Print the overall OOB confusion matrix
print(overall_OOB_conf_matrix)

for (i in 1:50) {
    set.seed(i)
    train_idx <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE)
    test_idx <- setdiff(1:n, train_idx)
    
    train_rf_class <- df_popular[train_idx, ]
    test_rf_class <- df_popular[test_idx, ]
    
    rf_model_class <- randomForest(popularity ~ ., data = train_rf_class, ntree = 100)
    phat <- predict(rf_model_class, test_rf_class, type = "prob")[, 2]
    
    roc_curve <- roc(test_rf_class$popularity, phat)
    AUC_rf[i] <- auc(roc_curve)
}

With a mean AUC of 0.72, the random forest algorithm outperforms the LPM and bagging models. The higher AUC indicates a stronger performance in ranking articles by their likelihood of being popular. # Access the confusion matrix from rf_model
rf_conf_matrix <- rf_model_class$confusion

# Calculate accuracy
rf_accuracy <- sum(diag(rf_conf_matrix)) / sum(rf_conf_matrix)

# Calculate precision
rf_precision <- rf_conf_matrix[2, 2] / sum(rf_conf_matrix[, 2])

# Calculate recall (sensitivity)
rf_recall <- rf_conf_matrix[2, 2] / sum(rf_conf_matrix[2, ])

Conclusion

In analyzing the Online News Popularity dataset, several key findings and insights emerged, providing valuable insights for content creators aiming to enhance article popularity on Mashable.

The Random Forest regression model emerged as the top performer in article shares prediction, compared to bagging and GBM, with a lower RMSE of 10655.42. Notably, the models effectiveness was underscored by a root mean squared percentage error of 506.59, showcasing its capability to predict popularity with a high level of accuracy. Feature importance analysis revealed that articles referencing themselves, along with those containing average and popular keywords, significantly influence article shares. Content creators should prioritize these aspects when crafting articles to maximize their potential for popularity.

Similarly, the Random Forest classification model demonstrated superior performance, outperforming both the Linear Probability Model (LPM) and bagging models with a mean AUC of 0.72. The models robustness was further validated by its lower Out-of-Bag (OOB) rate, indicating improved generalization and discrimination abilities. Notably, features related to average and popular shares of articles, particularly self-referenced ones, emerged as the most influential in predicting article popularity.

The analysis underscores the importance of self-referenced articles and the strategic use of average and popular keywords in driving article popularity on Mashable. Content creators should focus on incorporating these elements into their content strategy to maximize engagement and shares. Additionally, leveraging the insights gained from predictive modeling can inform editorial decisions and optimize content creation processes.

Despite the success of the models, challenges such as data quality and the dynamic nature of online content popularity were encountered. Future research could explore more sophisticated modeling techniques and incorporate real-time data streams to enhance predictive accuracy. Additionally, further investigation into user engagement patterns and preferences could provide deeper insights into factors driving article popularity.

In summary, this project utilized regression and classification models to predict article popularity on Mashable, yielding actionable insights for content creators. The Random Forest models emerged as top performers, emphasizing the significance of self-referenced articles and keyword optimization in driving engagement. By leveraging these findings, content creators can tailor their strategies to enhance article popularity and audience engagement, ultimately maximizing the impact of their content on online platforms.
